Short View Summary\
Usual Adult Dose\
\'95 Norfloxacin: oral (PO) 400 mg every 12 hours\
\'95 Ciprofloxacin: PO 250\'96750 mg every 12 hours; intravenous (IV) 200\'96400 mg every 12 hours\
\'95 Ofloxacin: PO or IV 200\'96400 mg every 12 hours\
\'95 Levofloxacin: PO or IV 250\'96750 mg daily; 240-mg nebulizer solution (available outside United States)\
\'95 Moxifloxacin: PO or IV 400 mg daily\
\'95 Gemifloxacin: PO 320 mg daily\
\'95 Delafloxacin: PO 450 mg every 12 hours; IV 300 mg every 12 hours\
Renal and Hepatic Failure: Decrease Dose in Renal Failure for All Except Moxifloxacin\
\'95 Cerebrospinal fluid penetration: low\
\'95 Adverse effects\
\'95 Common: gastrointestinal upset, central nervous system stimulation\
\'95 Less common: seizures, tendinitis and tendon rupture, Clostridioides difficile (formerly Clostridium difficile) disease, dysglycemia, exacerbations of myasthenia gravis, peripheral neuropathy\
\'95 Contraindications: prior quinolone allergy, prior neuropathy\
Drug-Drug Interactions\
\'95 Do not take oral formulations with aluminum-, calcium-, magnesium-, or iron-containing compounds.\
\'95 Avoid other agents that prolong the QT interval (particularly with moxifloxacin).\
\'95 Avoid concomitant use of tizanidine.\
\'95 Variable interactions occur with warfarin; monitor international normalized ratio.\
Indications (US Food and Drug Administration Approved)\
\'95 Norfloxacin: used to treat uncomplicated and complicated urinary tract infections and prostatitis. Can be used for urethral or cervical gonorrhea only if infecting isolates are known to be susceptible.\
\'95 Ciprofloxacin: used to treat complicated and uncomplicated urinary tract infections, chronic bacterial prostatitis, uncomplicated cervical and urethral gonorrhea (only if infecting isolates are known to be susceptible), complicated intra-abdominal infections, bacterial diarrhea, typhoid fever, acute bacterial sinusitis, lower respiratory tract infections (when not caused by Streptococcus pneumoniae), inhalational anthrax, skin and skin structure infections, and bone and joint infections.\
\'95 Ofloxacin: used to treat complicated and uncomplicated urinary tract infections, bacterial prostatitis, uncomplicated cervical and urethral gonorrhea (only if infecting isolates are known to be susceptible), nongonococcal urethritis and cervicitis caused by Chlamydia trachomatis, acute pelvic inflammatory disease, acute bacterial exacerbations of chronic bronchitis, community-acquired pneumonia, and uncomplicated skin and skin structure infections.\
\'95 Levofloxacin: used to treat complicated and uncomplicated urinary tract infections, acute pyelonephritis, chronic bacterial prostatitis, acute bacterial exacerbations of chronic bronchitis, community-acquired pneumonia, hospital-acquired pneumonia, inhalational anthrax, acute bacterial sinusitis, and complicated and uncomplicated skin and skin structure infections. Nebulizer solution used to treat chronic pulmonary infections due to Pseudomonas aeruginosa infections in patients with cystic fibrosis (outside United States).\
\'95 Moxifloxacin: used to treat community-acquired pneumonia, acute bacterial exacerbation of chronic bronchitis, acute bacterial sinusitis, and alternative agent in multidrug-resistant tuberculosis (off-label use).\
\'95 Gemifloxacin: used to treat community-acquired pneumonia and acute bacterial exacerbations of chronic bronchitis.\
