Figure 1. The illustration displays the chemical structures of selected quinolone antibiotics, starting with a labeled diagram of the quinolone core structure, a bicyclic ring system with numbered positions from one to eight. Beneath the core, eight different quinolone derivatives are illustrated, each showing variations in their side chains and substitutions on the core structure. These include nalidixic acid and norfloxacin at the top, followed by ciprofloxacin and levofloxacin, with the latter marked with an asterisk to highlight its asymmetric carbon. Ofloxacin is shown next to levofloxacin, labeled racemic mixture of stereoisomers. The third row includes moxifloxacin and gatifloxacin, both containing additional fused or cyclic groups. The final row includes delafloxacin, with chlorine and multiple fluorine atoms, and gemifloxacin, containing an amine and methoxy-substituted ring. Each compound retains the core quinolone structure with a carboxylic acid and ketone moiety while differing in the nature and position of attached functional groups.\
